<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / International Company News: Record capital increase at
Banesto
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANESTO, the large Spanish commercial bank, is to make a capital increase
worth some Pta130bn (Dollars 1.12bn), the largest in Spanish history, in a
three-stage plan co-ordinated with J. P. Morgan.
The plan, early details of which were made public in February, would be used
to strengthen the bank's capital base. Its BIS ratio would rise from 9.3 per
cent to 12 per cent. A weak capital base has long been a drag on Banesto's
profitability, analysts say.
Banesto said the three phases of the plan, which had also attracted a
promised investment from GE Capital, would involve:
A three-for-one rights issue, announced in February, designed to raise
Pta52.66bn in new capital. New shares would be priced at Pta1,500. J. P.
Morgan's Dollars 1bn Corsair bank fund will invest Dollars 200m in this
issue, offering an extra Pta400 per share for subscription rights. This
could give the fund a stake of close to 10 per cent in Banesto. Mr Mario
Conde, Banesto president, will also subscribe to the issue to raise his
personal holding of 2 per cent. If the Corsair fund is unable to spend all
Dollars 200m on the rights issue it would commit the remainder to the second
phase;
A placement, with investors, of 22.2m shares worth Pta42.25bn. Some Dollars
20m of this will be shares distributed by the bank to employees priced at
Pta1,900. Banesto said this was 27 per cent more than current shareholders
had paid but the bank's stock closed in Madrid yesterday at Pta2,350.
Banesto also said GE Capital and Northwestern Mutual would invest Dollars
25m each while an investor group led by Mr Jose Roquette, president of Banco
Totta &amp; Acores, the Portuguese bank bought by Banesto two years ago, would
spend Dollars 50m. A Dollars 400m convertible bond issue abroad. Banesto
said the five-year bonds would carry a coupon of between 6 and 7 per cent
and would help increase its second-tier capital.
Although some analysts in Madrid questioned how easily the bank would meet
its dividend obligations next year to a much wider group of shareholders,
the plans have been greeted positively. The presence of J. P. Morgan as
leader of the Corsair group has lent credibility to the operation.
Banesto's successful sale earlier this year of its Banco de Madrid affiliate
to the Deutsche Bank for Pta42bn has also greatly strengthened market
confidence in the bank.
It was, nevertheless, being vague last night about what it intended to do
with the money it was raising, saying, among other things, that it wanted to
attract first rate shareholders, to strengthen collaboration with Banco
Totta and to unite the interests of the board and the bank's workforce.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Banco Espanol de Credito.
</CO>
