<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / UK Company News: Observer board backs sale to Guardian
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BOARD of The Observer, which includes independent directors, yesterday
gave its unanimous backing to a sale of the Sunday title to The Guardian and
Manchester Evening News.
A statement issued last night said: 'The Observer board agreed unanimously
that negotiations should proceed towards early finalisation of a contractual
agreement with The Guardian.'
Neither Observer directors nor Guardian management would comment further.
The deal agreed in principle, however, is believed to value The Observer at
about Pounds 27m - a sum that would be paid to Lonrho, owner of The
Observer, over two years.
Any transfer of ownership to GMEN would require the permission of Mr Michael
Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, under the provisions of the Fair
Trading Act relating to newspaper mergers.
A reference to the Mergers and Monopolies Commission is automatic unless Mr
Heseltine is satisfied the paper was not economic as a going concern and
that the case is urgent.
The Observer is a loss-making paper but Mr Heseltine has made it clear to
parliament that he could not reach a view until he can study the terms of
any application.
</TEXT>
