<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / Lasmo compensates former chief executive with Pounds 2.2m
pay-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR CHRIS Greentree, who was replaced as chief executive of Lasmo, the
lossmaking independent oil company, last January, has received a pay-off
totalling Pounds 2.2m. Under an agreement announced yesterday, the
Canadian-born executive is also to receive Pounds 44,000 to cover
repatriation and other expenses.
Lasmo said it is paying Mr Greentree Dollars 1,233,500 (Pounds 785,000) for
loss of office. He had two years of a three-year contract to run.
He will also receive the benefit of various insurance policies and pension
entitlements which are expected to provide him with a pension of Dollars
189,000 a year. The value of the insurance policies, built up over 10 years,
is about Dollars 2.2m. The existence of the policies had not previously been
disclosed, a spokeswoman for the company said yesterday.
Mr Greentree was ousted from Lasmo after the company reported a loss of
Pounds 385m and cut its dividend due to heavy borrowing costs. In his last
year at the company he was paid a total of Pounds 480,647 including a Pounds
50,000 performance bonus, an increase of 40 per cent.
After his departure, senior Lasmo executives took a 5 per cent pay cut. Mr
Greentree's successor, Mr Joe Darby, was to be paid Pounds 200,000, the
company said at the time.
Mr Greentree's payment exceeds the deal agreed between British Petroleum and
its former chief Mr Bob Horton, who left the company last summer. Mr Horton
received a Pounds 1.5m package of compensation and pension entitlements.
</TEXT>
