FT  05 MAY 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dispatches (C4, 9.00) presents fresh and important evidence that the
government knowingly permitted British businessmen to sell arms to Iraq, and
then sold them down the river. Paul Grecian and his fellow accused were
arrested in October 1990 and were found guilty last year of breaking the
arms embargo. Their unsuccessful defence, that the government knew of and
abetted their activities, was the same which subsequently got the Matrix
Churchill defendants off. Grecian relates how his discoveries about Saddam's
supergun led to his becoming an unpaid informer for M15 and M16. Open Space:
The Price of Fish (BBC 1, 7.40) gives a mouthpiece to the fishermen of
Brixham and Grimsby and their grievances against the EC quota system. Living
Islam (BBC2, 8.10), reports on a subject about which much rubbish is talked,
namely the position of women in Islam. Pigs are enthusiastic omnivores. So
are humans, which adds a certain piquancy to the report on Tomorrow's World
BBC 1, May 5) that the Dutch have discovered how to feed pigs on their own
manure.
