<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour highlights local authority
job losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEARLY 38,000 job losses have been announced in local government in the past
five months, Labour said yesterday as the local election campaign entered
its final stage.
Launching a Labour-commissioned study of local government job losses, Mr
Jack Straw, shadow environment secretary, said local authorities in every
region of the country had been affected.
According to the report, conducted by the Centre for Local Economic
Strategies, a total of 6,000 job losses have been announced in Yorkshire and
Humberside, with 5,500 in the east Midlands and 5,400 in greater London.
More than 12,500 of the job losses are in county councils, which, the study
says, have 'borne the brunt' of council cuts along with metropolitan
authorities.
With voters in 47 county councils in England and Wales due to go to the
polls tomorrow, the Conservatives countered by saying that Tory policies
provided high-quality services in councils across the country at the lowest
price.
Mr Michael Howard, environment secretary, said voters should ask themselves
who would keep their bills down over the next four years and who would
'strive ceaselessly' for value for money.
In Northamptonshire, where Wellingborough district council recently set the
country's lowest council tax, Mrs Gillian Shephard, employment secretary,
said the assertion that Conservative councils cost you less and serve you
better was 'not just a slogan - it's the truth'.
The remarks were targeted at the central plank of Labour's campaign: that
average council tax bills are Pounds 14 lower in Labour councils than their
Tory counterparts.
</TEXT>
