<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: PM rejects oil tax criticisms
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday rejected criticism of the government's controversial
proposals for reforming the North Sea tax regime, saying they would be good
for jobs and good for Britain.
The prime minister said the reform would improve development incentives.
He was responding to criticism from Mr Robert Hughes, Labour MP for Aberdeen
North, who said the changes would 'savagely attack' small companies in the
drilling and exploration sector.
Under the Budget proposals, the rate at which petroleum revenue tax is
levied would fall from 75 per cent to 50 per cent and tax relief would be
abolished for exploratory drilling.
