<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: House to rule on criteria for Emu
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT con-firmed last night that the House of Commons would have an
opportunity to determine whether Britain was able to meet the European
Community's convergence criteria before embarking on economic and monetary
union under the Maastricht treaty, Ivor Owen writes.
Mr Stephen Dorrell, the financial secretary to the Treasury, announced that
the government would provide for the necessary parliamentary proceedings by
agreeing to add a new Labour clause, subject to some technical changes, to
the Maastricht bill.
He also gave a further assurance that the treaty did not impose an
obligation on the government to return sterling to the European exchange
rate mechanism.
Mr Andrew Smith, a shadow treasury minister, hailed the announcement as a
'victory' and stressed that in reaching a judgment on the convergence
criteria MPs could take account of the effect on budget deficits and the
general co-ordination of economic policy.
Mr Tristan Garel-Jones, foreign office minister, confirmed last night that
as a result of its earlier defeat on the Maastricht bill the government
would appoint members of local councils to all 24 places allocated to
Britain on the EC's committee of the regions.
</TEXT>
