<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Council members for Euro committee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Tristan Garel-Jones, foreign office minister, confirmed last night that
as a results of its earlier defeat on the Maastricht bill the government
would appoint members of local councils to all 24 places allocated to
Britain on the European Community's committee of the regions, Ivor Owen
writes.
As the report stage of the measure got under way, the government's
acceptance that it could not revive its original proposal that
businesspeople should be included among the British representatives on the
committee was hailed as 'surrender' by Mr George Robertson from the Labour
front bench.
He stressed that during the committee stage the government had been defeated
on a Labour amendment requiring all the British members of the committee to
be elected concillors in spite of having entered into a 'conspiracy' with
Scottish and Welsh nationalist MPs.
Mr Robertson's claim that the nationalist parties had got nothing out of
their deal with the government was disputed by Mr Ieuan Wyn Jones (Plaid
Cymru Yns Mond) and Mrs Margaret Ewing (SNP Moray).
In a series of clashes, Mr Jones emphasised that although claiming to
support the Maastricht treaty Mr Robertson and his colleagues had voted 38
times with the Tory rebels who wanted to wreck it.
MR Garel-Jones said the government would consult all the political parties
before deciding on the composition of the British contingent on the
committee of the regions.
</TEXT>
