<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / Miners hope to create 900 jobs in recycling joint venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Union of Democratic Mineworkers has joined forces with Vista
Partnership, a private consortium, in a venture aiming to create up to 900
jobs for former miners in environmental projects.
The two announced yesterday that they had formed a company, Vista-UDM, which
will build domestic waste recycling and disposal facilities on the sites of
abandoned pits - initially those of Cotgrave and Silverhill in
Nottinghamshire.
The schemes involve the creation of a plant to convert unsorted waste into
an absorbent aggregate used in industry, construction and land reclamation,
as well as a car recycling business in collaboration with BMW, the German
carmaker. The company estimates it will produce annual net exports worth
about Pounds 50m.
Formal negotiations on the projects are scheduled to begin with British Coal
on May 13. Informal talks have already been held with Mr Tim Eggar, the
energy minister, which the UDM said had been 'extremely positive'.
The union expects to secure grants from the government and the European
Community to establish the business.
Meanwhile, it emerged that more than 13,000 miners have left British Coal
since October, 2,600 of them in the past week. The latest voluntary
redundancies leave British Coal with less than 25,000 blue-collar employees.
British Coal has already achieved more than half the 25,000 manual job cuts
it sought through mine closures last October in spite of the scaling-back of
the mine- closure programme from 31 to 19 pits.
The redundancies are being taken on a voluntary basis and represent a
setback for unions which are still fighting closures. Disputes over British
Coal's closure consultation procedures are expected to return to the High
Court in the next few weeks.
This, however, is unlikely to save any of the pits. Miners at some
collieries, including Shirebrook, Rossington, Houghton Main, Markham Main
and Easington have already voted to accept local deals on improved
redundancies. British Coal says this signifies approval for closure.
Under the local deals, negotiated in the past few weeks, some miners will
gain up to Pounds 8,000 more than under the national deal. This is lifting
the average payment to above the previous Pounds 26,000.
</TEXT>
