<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / House prices are 'poised to recover'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSE PRICES showed a modest rise of 0.1 per cent last month according to
Nationwide, Britain's second-largest building society.
The figure represents the second consecutive monthly rise, but March's
increase was 1 per cent.
Mr Brian Davis, Nationwide's operations director, said: 'Overall, we have
seen little change in house prices over the last six months and this month's
figure is further evidence that stability is now returning to the housing
market.'
Mr Davis expected growing confidence over the next few months with
house-price recovery aided by first-time buyers entering the market.
The average UK house price in April was Pounds 52,339, 5.8 per cent lower
than the same month last year, said Nationwide.
Meanwhile, there were 218,867 residential property transactions in the first
quarter of this year - 4 per cent lower than the last quarter of 1992 and 8
per cent lower than last year's first quarter, according to the Adams
Residential Property Index. This is compiled by James R. Adams, a market
research consultancy, by monitoring housing completions made by solicitors.
Activity in construction remains low but the decline in quantity surveyors'
workload has begun to slow, says a survey published today by the Royal
Institution of Chartered Surveyors. Quantity surveyors' workloads fell 0.7
per cent in the first quarter of this year, compared with a 5 per cent drop
in the final quarter of 1992. Workload over the past 12 months has fallen 13
per cent.
