<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / Nissan accused over fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR executive from Nissan Motor Corporation, the Japanese car maker,
made the business introduction for the setting up of a Swiss bank account
which the Inland Revenue claims was part of a Pounds 97m corporation tax
fraud, an Old Bailey jury heard yesterday.
Mr Friedrich Pannosch, an Austrian rail consultant, was giving evidence in
the trial of Mr Michael Hunt, the Nissan UK director accused of taking part
in the fraud. The prosecution claims that directors of Nissan UK, the
British importer of Nissan cars, and others, inflated freight charges to
avoid tax and laundered money through shipping agents into Swiss bank
accounts.
Mr Pannosch is accused of involvement in the conspiracy but he has not been
charged.
Mr Pannosch, a prosecution witness, said he was introduced to Mr Tore
Thorsen, a Norwegian shipping agent, who is one of the other alleged
conspirators, by a Mr Yoshiro Saegusa, a senior executive with Nissan Japan.
Mr Pannosch told Mr Michael Sherrard QC, counsel for Mr Hunt, that Mr
Saegusa had said Mr Thorsen was helping Nissan Japan with transport
problems.
The Norwegian asked him to open an account in his own name because the
transactions could not be made directly and needed an intermediary. About
USDollars 200 passed through the account, the court heard.
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
