<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / Fresh competition powers welcomed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government's proposals to give the Office of Fair Trading tougher powers
to tackle monopolistic and anti-competitive behaviour have been warmly
welcomed by Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading.
In his first public statement on abuse of market power since the government
announced its preferred option for reform of the law last month, Sir Bryan
said he particularly welcomed the proposal to allow the director-general to
accept and enforce undertakings without carrying out a formal investigation.
In the magazine, In Competition, he said that in contrast to his power to
accept undertakings to allow mergers to go ahead without a reference to the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission, his power to accept non-statutory
assurances on anti-competitive behaviour had proved ineffective. The
extension of the 'fix it first' philosophy to anti-competitive behaviour
combined with tougher investigatory powers for the body should considerably
shorten the process of dealing with abuses of market power.
Businesses could not be pressurised into giving undertakings and the lack of
a full investigation might mean that other matters of concern were
overlooked. But that would be a price worth paying for speeding up the whole
process.
Mr Christopher Bright, a partner with City solicitors Linklaters &amp; Paines
and editor of In Competition, said Sir Bryan's statement was 'significant'
because it showed 'a new attitude to the use of the current law'. The 1980
Competition Act 1980 had not worked partly because the office had been too
cautious in enforcing it, he said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
