<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / Press moves to head off statutory controls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NEWSPAPER industry yesterday outlined steps to strengthen
self-regulation in an attempt to head off statutory controls.
The plans range from altering the membership of the Press Complaints
Commission to ensure a non-press majority, to the creation of a telephone
helpline for the public.
The helpline, to be run by the commission, will give immediate advice to
anyone fearing that the code of practice governing journalists' behaviour is
about to be breached. It will also provide the telephone and fax numbers of
the editors involved.
Mr Harry Roche, chairman of the Press Standards Board of Finance (Pressbof),
the body which co-ordinates the newspaper and magazine industry's actions on
self-regulation, said yesterday that the industry was 'totally opposed to
statutory regulation'. However, it recognised the need for a responsible
press which commanded the respect of the public.
The changes announced yesterday come in response to proposals for a
statutory press complaints commission from Sir David Calcutt, who chaired
the commission on the press and privacy. The Commons national heritage
committee has advocated a statutory press ombudsman, and the bill put before
parliament by Labour MP Mr Clive Soley proposed a press authority with
statutory powers.
In future the Press Complaints Commission, the self-regulatory body funded
by Pressbof, will be made up of eight non-press members, seven editors and
the independent chairman.
Mr Peter Preston, editor of The Guardian, said there should be talks across
the industry to see whether a common approach could be agreed on how
newsgatherers treat victims of tragedy.
The government has not yet announced its position apart from emphasising
that it plans to go ahead with measures to outlaw electronic eavesdropping
and the use of telephoto lenses on private property. Such measures are
accepted in principle by the industry as long as they apply to everyone and
not just to journalists.
</TEXT>
