<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / ITV seeks new era for broadcasting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ITV companies yesterday asked the government to look beyond the debate
on the future of the BBC and instead produce 'a new blueprint for a new
era'.
The television companies also argued for equality of treatment with cable
and satellite channels.
In their response to the government's green paper on the future of the BBC
the ITV companies call for:
Changes to ownership rules covering television.
A closing of the 'loophole' that allows News International to own 35 per
cent of the British national press and 50 per cent of British Sky
Broadcasting, the satellite venture in which Pearson, owner of the Financial
Times, has a stake.
Parity of regulation for all commercial broadcasters so that all cable and
satellite channels available in the UK would, like ITV, have to meet the EC
requirement for a minimum 51 per cent of programmes to be made in Europe.
In their submission to the National Heritage Department, the ITV companies
say that the 1990 Broadcasting Act which dealt with commercial television
was a retrospective document rather than a blueprint for a more volatile
future. ITV argues: 'The discussion leading to the next BBC charter in 1996
cannot make sense without careful consideration of the industry as a whole.'
The ITV case is backed by a study by consultants Booz Allen &amp; Hamilton on
the economic implications of the rapid changes in broadcasting. The
consultants argue that only 19 per cent of all programmes on channels
available in the UK last year were made in Europe. This could fall to 13 per
cent by the end of the decade.
Booz Allen says a 1991 trade deficit of Pounds 100m on television programmes
will rise to Pounds 640m by the end of the decade without government action.
Mr Greg Dyke, chairman of the ITV Association and LWT chief executive, said:
'If we're not careful the British television production industry could go
the same way as the British film industry.'
BBC transmitters should be privatised, ITV argues, to provide competition
for National Transcommunications, the Independent Broadcasting Authority's
privatised transmitting and engineering arm.
The ITV companies were unable to agree on whether they wanted an extension
of the moratorium on takeovers, which runs out at the end of this year.
Instead the government is asked to examine 'the existing ownership
regulations in broadcasting in the light of the major changes that are
likely to occur in the industry from the mid 1990s on'.
</TEXT>
