<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / Murdoch staff to vote on pay plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR RUPERT MURDOCH'S News International is balloting its employees, seeking
their agreement to a government-approved profit-related pay scheme.
The scheme would replace the annual salary review for the 1993-1994
financial year and might be extended for a further 12 months.
Under government regulations at least 80 per cent of all employees must
approve the proposal by May 19 for it to come into force. The maximum
tax-free PRP element of total pay can be 20 per cent or Pounds 4,000,
whichever is the lower.
News International is proposing that 15 per cent or Pounds 3,000 of an
employee's salary, whichever is the lower, will be the PRP element of their
pay.
The company says it will assume that anybody who does not vote in the ballot
approves of the scheme.
News International director Mr August Fischer, in a letter to employees,
says if the scheme is successful in the first year the company's 'present
intention would be to continue it for a second year and possibly expand the
scheme to the full tax-free PRP allowance'. He adds that the benefit of the
scheme will be that it can 'allow a greater rise in take-home pay than would
have been possible in any review, since inflation is running at such a low
rate'.
Someone earning Pounds 25,000 a year would be paid Pounds 3,000 of it in
PRP, equivalent to a Pounds 750 pay rise. More than 100 journalists working
on magazines published by Morgan Grampian will take a second consecutive day
of strike action today in protest at their employer's plan to de-recognise
the National Union of Journalists.
Morgan Grampian, which publishes magazines including The Engineer and Pulse,
said all titles would be published as planned.
</TEXT>
