<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / Workers face cut in injury payouts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYEES who are injured at work as the result of a crime could have the
amount of compensation they can claim cut by at least half because of
government plans to reform the Criminal Injuries Compensation Scheme, one of
the largest firms of trade union solicitors said yesterday.
A worker who is physically hurt or suffers psychological damage following an
assault or any other crime can at present claim compensation under the
scheme for loss of earnings as well as for the injury itself. Claimants
include assaulted teachers and firefighters hurt in fires caused by arson.
The government is expected in a white paper this summer to propose a new
'tariff' system for compensation. Victims would no longer have the severity
of their injuries assessed by experts; instead there would be a standard
scale of payments administered by civil servants. Actual loss of earnings or
the individual's personal circumstances would not be taken into account.
Robin Thompson &amp; Partners, a firm of solicitors which handles injury claims
for most public-sector unions, said it estimated that at least half of
current awards to employees under the scheme consisted of loss-of-earnings
payments.
The Home Office, which oversees the scheme, said there had been complaints
about delays in payments. The white paper would put forward ways of
streamlining the system and payments would in future 'reflect the
seriousness of the injury in round terms'.
A Sikh police officer yesterday accepted Pounds 25,000 compensation after
Nottinghamshire Constabulary admitted he had suffered racial discrimination.
Mr Joginder Prem told an industrial tribunal that he had suffered abuse
since joining the force in 1983 and that he had been passed over for
promotion to sergeant.
</TEXT>
