<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / 15 schools may be converted into City technology colleges
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 15 schools could be converted into city technology colleges next year
under plans being developed by the City Technology Colleges Trust.
The trust hopes to use a change to the law, introduced in the Education Bill
now before parliament, which will allow established schools to take
technology college status if they have opted out of local education
authority control. The colleges, introduced in the Education Reform Act of
1988, were at first intended to be purpose-built new schools funded only by
business sponsorship.
Under the trust's plans commercial sponsors would provide a minimum of
Pounds 50,000 a school, while the government would provide at least Pounds
200,000. This new route to technology college status is thought to offer
similar standards for a lower cost than that of a purpose-built college,
which requires backing of about Pounds 8m from companies.
Sir Cyril Taylor, chairman of the trust, said 31 schools had already been
approved to become technology college affiliates after increasing the length
of the school day and introducing more science and technology courses. He
said there was a backlog of schools wanting to apply. Between 10 and 15 of
the 31 will be put forward for full college status once the Education Bill
becomes law.
The Department for Education said yesterday that the criteria used to vet
each application had not yet been decided.
</TEXT>
