<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAY 93 / Changes to new fines system announced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GROWING concern over the effects of a new system of income-related fines
yesterday forced the government to announce changes to the Criminal Justice
Act only seven months after it came into force.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, home secretary, admitted after a meeting with magistrates
that the act had led to some 'absurd decisions' and needed to be amended.
The system of linking fines to income has resulted in some people with above
average earnings facing penalties of thousands of pounds for motoring
offences. In another celebrated case, an 83-year-old woman was fined Pounds
800 for not having a television licence, while the same court fined a
younger woman with a lower income Pounds 32.
Mr Clarke intends to retain the principle of unit fines linked to income,
but will reduce the banding on which the system operates. The disposable
income scales on which courts calculate fines range from Pounds 4 per week
to Pounds 100. 'I know of no tax or means-tested benefit where the spread is
1-25 so I would like to readdress that,' said Mr Clarke.
The Home Office believes some of the problems have arisen from courts
failing to appreciate the flexibility available under the new system. As an
immediate step, the government will emphasise to magistrates that they
should use the discretion open to them, pending legislation to change the
scale of fines.
Mr Clarke also intends to change another aspect of the wide-ranging act that
has been criticised by judges - limitations on courts being able to take an
offender's previous convictions into consideration when passing sentence. A
persistent reoffender was not the same as a first offender, said Mr Clarke,
and the courts should be able to take this into account.
The new arrangements have led to some magistrates resigning since they came
into effect in October. Ms Joyce Ross, who chairs the Magistrates'
Association, said after yesterday's meeting with Mr Clarke that the morale
of magistrates would be lifted by his proposals. 'Some of the changes cannot
happen overnight but at least we know there will be changes and they will be
in accord, we hope, with what we are proposing.'
The unit fine system was tested in four parts of the country without
apparent difficulty. But under the act maximum fines in magistrates' courts
rose from Pounds 2,000 to Pounds 5,000, and this has aggravated the problem.
Staff face cut in injury payouts, Page 7
More changes to the letter of the law, Page 17
</TEXT>
