<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Survey of Hong Kong (12): Emphasis on productivity -
Industrial development
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OF Asia's four dragons, Hong Kong is the only state whose government has not
tried to transform an efficient low-cost manufacturing base into a high
technology production line which can compete head-on with Japan and the US,
writes Simon Davies.
Fourteen year's after the door to China was opened, much of Hong Kong's
industrial heritage has been transferred into offices and shopping centres,
rather than gleaming new factories.
The laissez faire prop against which the Hong Kong government has leaned
since 1841, has prevented it from adopting the ambitious strategies that
spawned the computer components and telecommunications products of
Singapore, South Korea and Taiwan.
But as Hong Kong continues to evolve into a financial and services centre,
the pressures of some of the highest land and labour costs in Asia appear to
have give the government second thoughts about its stance.
Mr Ricky Fung, acting director general of the government's Industry
Department, stands by the philosophy of 'minimum intervention, maximum
support.' In spite of this, the government is taking serious measures to
encourage the inflow of overseas technologies, so that Hong Kong can retain
some kind of industrial base.
BY the end of December 1992, 565,100 people were employed in industry,
compared with 870,000 in 1986. Mr Fung said the government does not believe
in saving industries that are not competitive; in a territory which has to
import labour to meet the demands of a voracious economy, there is no
political pressures to save jobs.
Instead, the emphasis is on productivity rather than head count, and Hong
Kong has been faring well in this respect. Productivity increased by 18 per
cent last year, and it is now 80 per cent higher in real terms than it was a
in 1983.
This reflects the fact that the majority of industries have been relocating
production facilities, and those that cannot, have been replacing workers
with machinery. The resultant boost in productivity helped achieve a minimal
increase in domestic exports during 1992 to Dollars HK234bn.
This trend is continuing. Nomura Research Institute estimates that Hong Kong
retained imports of capital goods amounted Dollars HK73bn Kong last year,
indicating the level of new spending on machinery.
This represented an increase of more than 20 per cent from 1991 - outpacing
growth in retained imports of raw materials and consumer goods - and it
suggests that the outlook for productivity remains positive, in the
short-term at least.
In order to encourage this trend, the government has toned down its laissez
faire inclinations to permit a new applied research and development scheme.
This is a Dollars HK200m fund, which will match the investment of any
start-up company which fulfills certain criteria, in exchange for an equity
stake. This represents the first step towards direct government funding for
research and development, and by implication, the creation of a Government
industrial policy.
But it is a very tentative step, and local industrialists believe that in
the longer-term Hong Kong will not be able to compete in anything other than
niche manufacturing. Mr Patrick Wang, managing director of Johnson Electric
 -one of the world's largest manufacturers of micro-motors - says that as a
manufacturing base Hong Kong can be more meaningfully compared to
Switzerland than to other south-east Asian countries.
Johnson is one of the few Hong Kong industrial companies which has succeeded
in competing with the Japanese in high-technology production. It produces
motors for consumer electronics products and car accessories from plants in
China, Thailand and Switzerland.
The company still employs 1,000 people in Hong Kong, and this represents a
crucial base for leveraging the cheap production facilities in China, where
it employs 7,000 workers. But Mr Wang argues that 'to survive, we have to
think and act more like the Swiss.'
Johnson's plant in Switzerland has operating costs around double those of
Hong Kong, but the differential is shrinking fast. The key, according to Mr
Wang, is that Hong Kong has to focus on technical proficiency, rigid cost
control and more creative use of technology.
The government is making some effort to help this. It has provided a Dollars
HK250m grant for an Industry and Technology Centre, a new University of
Science and Technology was recently completed, and plans have been initiated
for a Dollars HK2.8bn science park (government contributions would be much
lower). In addition, its industrial estates in Tai Po and Yuen Long provide
land for high-tech industries at significantly below market rates.
But for many of Hong Kong's manufacturers becoming 'Swiss' is not an option.
Mr Jack Lau, managing director of Tomei International, one of Hong Kong's
largest consumer electronics manufacturers, argues that 'for the traditional
low-end manufacturers, there is no choice. Relocating to China is a matter
of survival'.
As industrialists gain further experience of China production, they are
finding that the workforce has more to offer than just cheap export
processing. Hong Kong companies are recruiting Chinese science graduates for
research and development projects, further replacing the role of Hong Kong's
domestic industry.
However, there have been a few successes in importing industry. The German
media giant, Bertelsmann, recently purchased a 55 per cent stake in
Sonopress Asia, a compact disc manufacturing company.
Mr Henry Chow, managing director of Sonopress, says the venture has been a
success, but its full potential is in the eventual opening up of the China
market. The company has capacity to manufacture 17m compact discs a year,
and already controls around 40 per cent of the Hong Kong market, but at
present China is effectively off-limits.
Mr Clive Weedon, head of research at Nomura, suggests that domestic
manufacturing is going into inevitable decline - 'as 1997 approaches, it is
difficult to envisage Hong Kong providing any more than support services for
the Pearl River delta, along with some specialised niche production.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
