<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Survey of Hong Kong (8): Pressures mount over 1997 - Alain
Cass on attitudes among the Hong Kong Chinese
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAIN CASS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HONG KONG is schizoid about 1997. This is hardly surprising. For 150 years
it has lived life in the fast lane, conditioned to thinking short-term.
Identifying with neither Britain nor China, life for Hong Kong Chinese
revolved around the family, the clan and money which they accumulated as if
there was no tomorrow. In a sense, there wasn't. If they didn't make it,
they just moved on.
All that is changing. Hong Kong is now having to come to terms with a future
which, for the first time, promises certainty: tomorrow is life as part of
the People's Republic of China and people are having to make up their mind
where they stand.
A recent survey of attitudes to the takeover underlined the paradox of Hong
Kong's situation. Most people were deeply gloomy about the future in
general. They foresaw a loss of freedom and a fall in their living
standards.
But asked how they and their families would fare personally they were much
more cheerful. Their children would have more opportunities because the
elite were leaving in their thousands, thus creating room at the top. South
China was taking off economically which meant jobs and business
opportunities.
Prof. Wong Siulin, who teaches social sciences at Hong Kong University,
expresses a different side of this split vision - 'I have always been deeply
ambivelant about China,' he says.' On the one hand, I am very suspicious of
its leadership. I was shocked by what happened at Tienanmen Square. But it
also matters a lot to me to be Chinese. The sense of unity is deeply
ingrained, not so much because China is a great power, although that is part
of it. It's far more a sense of history, a sense of family.'
He still remembers how, during Mao's Great Leap Forward which devastated
China, he would go, with his mother, to his local post office in Hong Kong
to send food parcels and cooking oil to relatives trapped in Guandong
province after the communist take-over. One of his uncles has since built a
house - for the two daughters he left behind - for Pounds 6,000, 'out of a
sense of guilt I think, as much as anything else.' For Hong and China, read
East and West Germany.
The dilemma for Hong Kong's Chinese community now is how to reconcile
China's emotional pull with the urge to develop a distinct local identity to
preserve its cherished freedoms. The events of June 4, 1989 when the
communist leadership ruthlessly snuffed out the student revolt in Peking,
provided a horrifying glimpse of a possible future. A million people poured
on to the streets to protest.
Political parties won a big boost as people began to think seriously, many
for the first time, about what they stood for and whether they had a future
in Hong Kong after 1997. Many concluded they did not - and voted with their
feet. The haemorrhage has been running at the rate of 60,000 a year.
Mr Chris Patten's arrival has provided a new rallying point. Politics has
become more focussed and more vociferous, but the absolute numbers who are
actively involved have not grown. Students, if anything, are becoming less
political. Student unions are having trouble filling posts. At an individual
level, young people have reverted to doing what comes naturally - bettering
themselves. Faced with the choice of the ideal and the practical, Hong Kong
man will almost invariably choose the latter.
Even ardent Patten supporters are inwardly divided. Their heart applauds his
eleventh-hour poker game, but their head tells them that, in the long run,
it may not make much difference.
'If we don't stand up to them now,' said the chairman of a big local
business over dinner,' they'll get away with murder when they take take over
 -maybe literally . . . but ultimately,' he concedes, 'Hong Kong cannot
confront China. We have to work with them.'
Like many others, he and his children have a 'parachute' - a British
passport and an overseas bank account.
At a deeper level there are few signs of social dislocation, given the
uncertainty which the territory faces.
Hong Kong society appears remarkably stable. It has a low suicide rate, an
enviably low and falling crime rate and a divorce rate which, while rising,
remains lower than that in comparable societies. Drugs is not a serious
problem in schools, although the Triads, Hong Kong's 'mafia,' are
everywhere.
Whether it stays that way is largely up to China. If, post-1997, Peking is
heavy-handed, or if it tries to dilute Hong Kong's local identity by
flooding the place with northerners, as it has done elsewhere on the
mainland to secure its grip, then there could be serious social tensions.
But if it adopts a cooler approach then an infinitely flexible Hong Kong
will merely adapt and learn to work a different system.
</TEXT>
