<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Survey of Hong Kong (4): Cautious hopes for big economic
rewards - Alain Cass examines Hong Kong's growing integration with China's
economy. Uncertainties are many and the stakes are high
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAIN CASS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHINA calls Hong Kong's transition to 1997 the 'through-train.' There are
few illusions in the colony about this journey into the unknown. Some
freedoms will go, if not overnight, then gradually.
The hope to which Hong Kong's workaholic business community clings is that
its no-holds-barred freedom to trade will not be among them.
This could be wishful thinking. The argument that, to sustain an open
economy in the long run you need a free flow of information, if not free
speech, is powerful and seductive, not least because of the poignancy of
Hong Kong's situation.
But things may not be as bleak as they seem on the surface - for two
reasons. The first is that a number of economies in the region have
flourished without democracy - Singapore, Taiwan and South Korea to name but
three. In the case of the last two, economic prosperity has smoothed the way
for a gradual change from martial law to a semblance of free elections.
The second reason for cautious optimism is that the Chinese are embracing
capitalism with evangelical fervour. Money is softening up the communist
party and Hong Kong is thriving on the back of this get-rich-quick culture.
It is one the great ironies of history that refugees who fled Mao Zedong's
prison camps after the communist take-over in 1949 now ebb and flow across
the border in their thousands, cutting deals with his successors. In his
inaugural address, Mr Chris Patten, Hong Kong's new governor, spoke of an
economic revolution, not seen since the industrialisation of Europe and
America, sweeping the region and carrying Hong Kong with it. Mr Hamish
Macleod, the colony's financial secretary, refers to growth in southern
China's ultra-liberated provinces as 'astonishing.'
Granted, these are worried men with a vested interest in talking up the
region's economic prospects. But the figures, even allowing for a healthy
margin of error, suggest the dreaded take-over may not be all bad or all
one-way:
Hong Kong-based businesses and their mainland partners now employ three
million people in over 25,000 factories in southern China. This vast
off-shore force of cheap labour is bigger than the colony's own working
population which is increasingly employed in the services sector. In a
recent survey, 70 per cent of the colony's electronics manufacturers said
they had invested in China.
An estimated 30 per cent of Hong Kong's total note and coin issue circulates
in southern China - about twice the amount of 18 months ago. Taxi drivers in
Shenzen, just across the border, accept Hong Kong dollars. Gold shops in the
colony will take Chinese currency.
China's economy grew by 12 per cent in real terms in 1992 and is forecast to
grow by at least 7 and 8 per cent this year, and possibly more. Southern
China will almost certainly vastly outpace the national average. This growth
has had a dramatic effect on Hong Kong. It is now the mainland's biggest
trading partner. China, in turn, is Hong Kong's best overseas customer,
pushing even the mighty US into second place.
Total contracted foreign investment in China by September 1992 was USDollars
78.6bn of which just over USDollars 25bn had been realised. Hong Kong
accounts for around two-thirds of that total, more in the south of the
country.
Hong Kong has become a significant market for capital flowing in and out of
mainland China. By the end of the decade, by some estimates, China-related
listings in the Hong Kong market will account for 45 per cent of its
capitalisation or as much as USDollars 900bn, up from USDollars 175bn in
1992.
For the sceptics who doubt these figures, there is the evidence of their own
eyes. The Pearl river delta is like a giagantic game of Monopoly, sprouting
factories, apartments and office towers. More than 18,000 trucks a day leave
Hong Kong's container port - the world's biggest - for China. Seven years
ago less than 12 per cent of the port's trade was with China. Last year it
reached 65 per cent and the proportion is still growing.
As one analyst put it, '1997 has already happened - it's just that the
politicians haven't noticed.'
Hong Kong's growing integration with the Chinese economy offers the prospect
of huge rewards. If the 'China Express' powers ahead, Hong Kong will
continue to ride high.
But growing dependence on China also carries some risks. Runaway inflation
and rampant corruption could drive the Chinese economy off the rails,
triggering social unrest, as happened in 1989, in which case Hong Kong would
be in for a rough ride.
CHINA is now in its third go-stop cycle since 1979, when Deng Xiaoping
abandoned the command economy. Inflation is running well into double-digit
figures - some say running away altogether. The widely-used unofficial rate
for the renminbi has fallen sharply. Rivalry between the centre and the
richer provinces could grow as these become economically more powerful and
demand greater autonomy. Inequalities of wealth could - almost certainly
will - lead to renewed social unrest sometime in the future.
There is already talk of the leadership tightening monetary policy again to
slow the rate of growth. A credit crunch in China would hit the colony hard.
Property developers hoping to cash in on China's chronic shortage of urban
housing, now that 1980's construction boom in Hong Kong is effectively over,
would suffer. So would its manufacturers of consumer goods.
Failure by the President Bill Clinton's administration to renew China's Most
Favoured Nation (MFN) status in June would slash growth in Hong Kong, which
is why Mr Patten will argue unconditionally for its renewal when he goes to
Washington. The colony's worst nightmare is a faltering US recovery, a
credit crunch in China and a suspension of Peking's MFN status.
The government hopes that at least two of these will not materialise. It
forecasts real GDP growth of 5.5 per cent this year, incidentally,
overtaking the UK in per capita terms. Despite objections from Beijing, or
perhaps because of them, the government is rushing to put in place as much
of the planned infrastructure as possible before 1997, using its substantial
reserves instead of resorting to tax increases. Domestic inflation is a
worry. This has fallen from its peak of nearly 14 per cent in 1991, but it
remains over 10 per cent which, the government concedes, is uncomfortable
high.
The Hong Kong dollar's fixed link with its US counterpart may anchor the
economy and keep it externally competitive, but it also hobbles the fight
against inflation by limiting the government's use of the interest rate
weapon.
For the past 10 years the currency's rate has been fixed at HKDollars 7.8 to
the USDollars . The territory's interest rates track US rates. These have
been low to boost America's anaemic economy. The effect on Hong Kong of low
interest rates has been to fuel stock and property market speculation,
boosting asset prices and inflation.
The expansionary budget, introduced by Mr Patten in February, has been
criticised for promoting inflation. Some economists, notably Mr John
Greenwood, chairman of GT Management, who fathered the link with the US
dollar, says high growth and the fixed exchange rate will save Hong Kong
from conventional inflation-sickness.
Nevertheless, soaring land and labour costs and the difficulty of recruiting
skilled labour to Hong Kong is driving some back-office services not just
across the border into China but elsewhere in the region. Cathay Pacific,
the colony's flagship airline, plans to set up an accountancy centre in
Guangzhou and a database in Australia to capitalise on cheap labour and
land.
The relentless migration of Hong Kong's young, middle-class professionals
ahead of 1997 chips away at its competitive edge. They are leaving at the
rate of 60,000 a year or nearly one per cent of a population which is barely
growing and getting older. Unless Hong Kong can find a way of replacing them
and developing its 'intelligent' core, it could find itself with a
manufacturing base largely in China and its high-value services dribbling
away to up-and-coming regional hubs.
In the long-run there is always the possibility of a sudden and
unpredictable lurch back to Mao's economics in China by a communist party
fearing loss of power and a Soviet-style break-up of the country. But the
risk of that happening decreases as the power of the Chinese consumer grows.
Ultimately the best - the only - guarantee of Hong Kong's economic survival
is for China's stake in the colony to become so big and the number of
officials who might wish to slam shut the open-door so outnumbered by those
who want to make money, that nothing else makes sense.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>HKZ  Hong Kong, Asia.
    CNZ  China, Asia.
</CN>
