<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Survey of Flanders (7): Backlash against traditional parties
 -A variety of protest votes in 1991 sent shock waves through Flanders
politics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLITICALLY, the last 18 months have been difficult for Flanders. When
Belgium went to the polls in November 1991, it was the northern part of the
country which suffered most from the backlash against traditional political
parties.
Vlaams Blok, a right-wing extremist party dedicated to the expulsion of
immigrants from Flanders, won 10.4 per cent of the regional vote - 25 per
cent in Antwerp - and more seats in the Flemish (and Belgian) parliaments
than the moderate Flemish nationalist party, the Volksunie.
Each of the dominant parties in Flanders, the Christian Democrats and
Socialists, saw support slip by more than 4 per cent. For good measure, an
anti-political party headed by maverick millionaire Jean-Pierre Van Rossem,
came from nowhere to capture 5.2 per cent of the vote and four seats on the
Flemish regional council. The shock result was not confined to the north,
but according to the caricature outsiders' view of Belgium (a country split
into two or more regions, Yugoslav-style, by absurd linguistic struggles and
dangerous extremism) Flanders was the real villain of the piece.
But at the same time, Flanders - with its increasing economic strength and
historic sense of identity - is well-placed to gain from constitutional
reforms edging their way through the Belgian parliament which devolve more
powers to the regions.
The question for traditional parties is how to take advantage of those
reforms without encouraging extreme Flemish nationalism which would further
tarnish the region's political reputation, particularly outside Belgium.
In opposition, the liberal PVV, headed by neo-Thatcherite Guy Verhofstadt,
has taken the most drastic step. In November last year it turned itself into
a new party, the VLD (liberal democrats), which is set to become the biggest
party in Flanders and Belgium.
The PVV was the only traditional party to gain votes in Flanders at the
election. Verhofstadt also cannily decided not to participate in the Flemish
government coalition, formed in February 1992 out of socialists and
Christian Democrats. It turned out to be shrewd move. An opinion poll
published at the end of last year in La Libre Belgique, one of Belgium's
francophone daily newspapers, indicated that the VLD was the most popular
party in Flanders, with a rating of 26.1 per cent, against 22.3 per cent for
the CVP.
Verhofstadt says he and his liberal colleagues were motivated to form the
VLD - a party for the citizen - when they realised that Belgium's
traditional ruling parties appeared to be taking little notice of the
popular 'protest vote' in the November 1991 poll. 'A million people voted
for extremist parties, and anti-political parties, and yet we've only
changed the prime minister and the (national) coalition is continuing with
the same policy,' he says.
The governing coalition in Flanders has taken a different tack. Inspired by
Luc Van den Brande, its Christian Democrat leader, the Flemish government
published in March a lengthy strategy document, Flanders-Europe 2002.
Van den Brande says the Flemish government wanted to encourage the people of
Flanders to abandon selfish short-termism and look to the future.
Concentrating on seven areas of strategy - from culture and employment
through to transport, education and housing - the document is an ambitious
attempt to lay out broad policy lines for the next decade.
On constitutional reforms, both Verhofstadt and Van den Brande agree that
they are only the most recent stage in a longer process which began over 20
years ago. 'This is an important step, and we should try to implement it
properly,' says Van den Brande, 'but it isn't the last step.'
Flanders has already achieved much autonomy through previous state reforms.
The region also has an advantage over its Walloon neighbour in that the
Flemish regional council and the Dutch-speaking community council have
merged into a single body, the Flemish council.
The Flemish government controls environment, housing, and energy policy,
industrial economic strategy, public works and transport, as well as
education, culture and welfare policy. This year's reform adds agriculture
and foreign trade to those powers.
It also provides for a directly elected Flemish parliament - in the current
system, national deputies also sit in the regional and community councils.
If there is a further round of constitutional reforms, most Flemish
politicians would like to see greater devolution of financial and fiscal
responsibility to Flanders, instead of the region having to rely on
donations from the central treasury.
Flemings also continually stress the need for a more 'balanced' approach to
welfare payments. At the moment social security is still managed by the
central state, but the wealthier residents of Flanders claim they are
underwriting social security payments to jobless Walloons.
It is probably still too soon for the angry political debate to become a
serious proposal for reform, but as one Flemish economist points out, the
devolution of education policy to the regions was an equally explosive issue
in the 1980s, but 'now it's regionalised and everyone is more or less happy
with it'.
How likely is it, then, that this gradual reform will end in a separatist
solution to Belgium's complex political problems, with Flanders, Wallonia
and Brussels - which is a region in its own right - going their own way?
Politicians from the Socialist, Christian Democrat and Liberal Democrat
parties in Flanders are in accord on this point. Most Flemings do not want
to cut themselves off from their southern neighbours, say the politicians,
but they do want a 'fair, federalist solution,' for practical as much as
sentimental reasons, based on dialogue between regions and communities.
It sounds like common sense. But in practice, all Belgian politicians like
to keep a little separatist rhetoric up their sleeves, just in case dialogue
turns into confrontation, as it often has in the past.
In addition, neither Flanders nor Wallonia is a static political entity,
waiting for reform to happen. Both are hyperactive self-promoters, pinning
their hopes on a role for the regions within Europe, rather than clinging on
to the apron-strings of Mother Belgium.
Mr Van den Brande, for example, has already published a strategy document
which lays out a Flemish 'foreign policy', ahead of the latest reforms,
which give the regions the ability to sign international treaties in their
own policy areas.
In this international public relations battle, the success of extremists in
the 1991 election was a clear setback for Flanders. Next year's municipal
elections in Antwerp and other cities may indicate the extent to which the
extremist vote was merely a symptom of wider popular disgruntlement.
In the meantime, the more moderate politicians in Flanders can only hope
that renewed Flemish pride will manifest itself in an outward-looking,
entrepreneurial spirit, rather than in unattractive, inward-looking
nationalism.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
               Popularity of Flemish political parties (%)
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
PARTY                          NOV '91     SEPT '92     DEC '92
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Liberal democrats (VLD)            19%       22.5%*        26.1
Christian democrats (CVP)         26.9         23.6        22.3
Socialists (SP)                   19.6         17.4        16.3
Vlaams Blok                       10.3         11.9        11.4
Agalev (greens)                    7.8         10.8        10.9
