<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Survey of Flanders (9): Smart in every sense - Guy
Verhofstadt leads a fast-growing political party
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GUY Verhofstadt, leader and architect of the VLD, Belgium's newest and
fastest growing political party, is young and sharp-suited. He is, in every
sense, a smart politician.
The Flemish liberal party (PVV) he headed was one of the only established
political parties to gain parliamentary seats at Belgium's last election, in
November 1991. At that election, voters demonstrated their disgust for the
machinations of traditional party politics in Belgium by backing extremist,
green and anti-political parties.
In the chaotic aftermath, Mr Verhofstadt realised that the PVV would have to
do more than rest on its laurels. 'We analysed the political situation in
the country and decided it was necessary to build up what we call a
democratic alternative to the present government,' he says.
The result was the Flemish liberal democrat party (VLD) - 'Partij van de
Burger' the party of the citizen - which was born almost exactly a year
after the election. One of its aims is to break the stranglehold which, Mr
Verhofstadt says, pressure groups - notably the unions - have over the
Flemish and French-speaking Christian Democrat and socialist parties which
form the current coalition.
Other goals include cutting expenditure without raising taxes, encouraging
Belgians to invest some of their extensive savings to help growth, and
capping wage increases.
The similarities with the radical conservatism of Mrs Margaret Thatcher are
not coincidental. Since the late 1970s the PVV had been a zealous backer of
the free market, and Verhofstadt, who took over as leader in 1982, was a
keen follower of Thatcherite and Reaganite principles. He is still a regular
visitor to the free-market Adam Smith Institute in the UK; he says the VLD
has taken on some of those traits, adapting them to the Belgian system and
adjusting them to take into account the mistakes which both Thatcher and
Reagan made.
The VLD started with an advantage in the opinion polls over the Flemish
Christian Democrats (CVP). Mr Verhofstadt says it has been adding new
members from across the political spectrum, including many who have never
before been involved in politics.
The confidence of the new party and its leader is unquestioned. When
Belgium's centre-left government was teetering on the brink of collapse in
March, Guy Verhofstadt was not afraid to call for immediate elections,
despite the risk that a new poll would simply aggravate the electorate's
disgruntlement with traditional politics.
Whether the VLD can go on building on its strong foundations depends to a
large extent on Verhofstadt himself, who finds himself on the right of the
party he has helped to create. Just turned 40, a lawyer by training, he
already has a ministerial career on his curriculum vitae: he was a tough
budget minister and vice-premier between 1985 and 1988.
But some say Verhofstadt is too tough, and are critical of his autocratic
management style. He was one of the senior Belgian politicians asked by the
King to forge a coalition after the 1991 election. His reluctance to
compromise - a serious flaw in the Byzantine world of Belgian politics - was
one reason why he failed.
Verhofstadt himself is not a separatist, although he says there is a risk
that the country will split if Belgium's regions are not given more fiscal
and financial autonomy - a central plank of the VLD manifesto.
But he sees his own political future as a national rather than a regional
deputy. The VLD's policy is founded on a rigorous economic programme, and,
as he points out, 'the economy, fiscal policy, and European economic and
monetary union are all problems discussed at federal, not regional level'.
If he mellows enough to become a prime minister, it will probably be of
Belgium rather than Flanders.
</TEXT>
