<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Survey of Flanders (2): Europe on a Flemish stage - Antwerp,
a city which mixes brio with introversion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANTWERP 93, the arts festival nearly a year long which began at the end of
last month, marks the ancient port's turn as the European city of culture.
It is 'very much a European programme performed on a Flemish stage,' in the
words of Mr Bob Cools, the city's ebullient socialist mayor.
But 1993 could be an even more defining year for Antwerp. It is attempting
to rediscover its roots as an open city, at a time when it is under great
pressure to turn inwards, and become a narrow and xenophobic capital of
intolerant Flemish nationalism.
The two golden ages of Antwerp were the 16th and 17th century - after Bruges
silted up and Antwerp replaced it as the trading hub and great port of the
north - and the 19th century, when it began to establish itself as the
diamond centre of the world it is now.
The port and the diamond trade remain pivots of Antwerp's local economy.
Together they employ 100,000 people, with the port contributing 3.2 per cent
of Belgian GNP, and diamonds accounting for 7 per cent of Belgium's exports.
But they helped underwrite the extraordinary artistic flowerings of the
golden ages, best marked by the early 17th century trio of master painters,
Rubens, Van Dyck and Jacob Jordaens; and by the art nouveau architectural
jewels that stud the city in fin de siecle flights of fancy.
In the view of Mr Eric Antonis, the theatre director in charge of the
Antwerp 93 programme, the best periods of the city's past were 'when it was
an open, cosmopolitan entrepot; the worst were when we were a closed city.'
He, as well as Mr Cools, acknowledges that the city has always been an
uncomfortable mix of metropolitan brio and provincial introversion.
Himself a native of Turnhout near the Dutch border, who has made most of his
theatre career in Amsterdam, Mr Antonis has brought to his job a faith in
Antwerp's best traditions. 'I have never seen a people so in love with their
city,' he says.
But the most stressed recent fact about Antwerp is an ugly one. In the 1991
elections, one out of every four of its inhabitants voted for the Vlaams
Blok - a party of extreme-right Flemish nationalists who want to turn the
city into a Flemish-only enclave. Under the chilling slogan Eigen Volk Eerst
 -'Our People First' - and flying in the face of a history of wealth
generated by Italian, English, German, Jewish and Dutch merchants, the Blok
wants to deport the city's Moroccan and Turkish immigrants, who together
amount to a mere 20th of Antwerp's population of 465,000.
Optimists see the vote as a protest against the parochial squabbles of the
traditional parties, divided across Belgium into Dutch and French-speaking
clans of Christian Democrats, Socialists and Liberals, rather than the
emergence of Antwerp as a fascist citadel.
Mayor Cools says: 'I think that the people in this city who voted for the
Blok must feel a little ashamed. I hope people are opening their eyes to
what the Blok is, and how damaging it is to give Antwerp the reputation of
an extreme right-wing city. After all, we are a port, a city which is
supposed to be open to the rest of the world.'
The Antwerper, Mr Cools insists, is not like that. 'He knows that when he
puts his hand in the water, he is in contact with the entire world.'
Yet the tension spilled over minutes after Antwerp 93's opening last month -
and in a televised clash between Mr Antonis and Mr Cools; men essentially on
the same side of the argument.
Mr Antonis had brought in a Frenchman to stage Antwerp 93's opening
fireworks display, overlooking the rival claim of a local pyrotechnician.
The Frenchman opted for a difficult spectacle to emphasise the role of the
River Scheldt in the city's life, with the fireworks hanging low over the
water. Only a fraction of the 400,000 people who turned up could actually
see it.
The mayor attacked the director for not employing the local man. Mr Antonis
shot back angrily: 'That sounds a bit like Eigen Volk Eerst.'
Mr Antonis says he regrets the outburst. But he insists that there is a
contradiction to be answered between the spirit of a truly international
arts festival and the anti-foreigner animus stirred up by the Vlaams Blok.
'My answer is our history,' he says, adding that 'art is a bit like
society's research department.'
Among the exhibitions pleasing him most is a history of Antwerp as an open
metropolis in the 16th and 17th century, 'with pieces of art telling the
story.' Second, probably, comes the floating theatre constructed on the
Scheldt. Companies from 14 cities will each work in residence for a week,
showing theatre, dance and video, 'telling us what is going on in St.
Petersburg and Johannesbourg, Los Angeles and Ljubljana, Marseilles and
Stockholm.'
The big Jordaens exhibition at the Museum of Fine Arts, marking the 400th
anniversary of the local master's birth - is the first real overview of his
work.
Again, Mr Antonis sees the exhibition as evidence of the strength of
openness working out of strong local roots. He is hoping that it will dispel
the 'slightly provincial image' Jordaens has, partly because of Rubens and
Van Dyck's more universal renown.
The year's programme for Antwerp 93 is studded with attractions, from newly
commissioned contemporary operas to steel bands. A permanent fashion centre
will show off a brilliant new generation of Antwerp designers.
In June, the Diamond High Council is putting on an exhibition of unique
jewellery, much of it unseen, from private collections, including Romanov
showpieces let out of the Kremlin for the first time.
All this in a city with a rich variety of good food and drink in some 2,500
restaurants and bars: the expected 3m visitors can sup and quaff in settings
ranging from the renaissance Grote Markt to the art nouveau Cogels-Osylei,
from Chinatown to the riverside.
Rather like Barcelona, with the Olympic Games, Antwerp is - on a more modest
scale - using the festival to refurbish; restoring the city's turn-of-the
century train station, the magnificent 19th century Bourla theatre, and the
cathedral.
The streets are clean, the facades and the trams are bright and gleaming,
and Mr Cools has deftly pedestrianised about a fifth of the inner city. 'I
fought for years for that,' he says, 'but thanks to 1993 I had the
possibility to push it through at last.'
Also like Barcelona, which used the Olympics to rediscover its waterfront,
the Stad aan de Stroom (City on the River) scheme - two building
developments intended to re-attach the river to the city it gave life to -
has been revived by Antwerp 93, partly supervised by a Barcelona architect.
But the most lingering effect sought by Mr Antonis is to make Antwerpers
'proud of their tradition as an open city,' which 'maybe - I say maybe -
could lead to a return of more political openness.' The Blok called a press
conference just after Antwerp 93 opened, to denounce it as propaganda
directed against the party. Aside from the fireworks - damp squibs - Antwerp
93 may be succeeding.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BEZ  Belgium, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
