<PROFILE>_AN-DEDCCAEWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930504
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Survey of Flanders (1): Sensitive barometer - Belgium's
prosperous and populous Flemish region is seeking new ways to exploit its
trading advantages within the EC without aggravating separatist tensions or
far-right extremists. As Antwerp takes its turn as the cultural capital of
Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF PEOPLE beyond Belgium's borders know anything about Flanders, it is
probably that it was once a bloody first world war battlefield.
Nowadays, however, most Flemish people want the northern half of Belgium to
be synonymous with economic and industrial progress, culture, and free
trade, washed down with a large draught of political autonomy. 'The golden
passport to Europe' is the slogan chosen by the Flemish external relations
administration to promote the region.
This should be a good year for the public and domestic image of Flanders.
Antwerp took over from Madrid at the end of March as Europe's cultural
capital. Flanders Technology International - an international science fair,
showcase for the region's high-tech industries - celebrates its 10th
birthday in Ghent this week.
Meanwhile, the national parliament is passing a series of measures which
will devolve even more power to Belgium's regions - Flanders, Wallonia and
Brussels. And the Flemish regional government has launched
'Vlaanderen-Europa 2002', an ambitious effort to lay out a strategy for
Flanders over the next decade, placing the region at the heart of a
tripartite decision-making structure: local authorities, regions and the
European Community.
But even in 1993 Flanders is a battlefield for opposing forces. On the one
side, the reasoned discourse of the majority, talking moderation and
federalism, Belgian-style; on the other, the more strident tones of minority
separatists and nationalists. The challenge for the Flemish moderates is to
neutralise their more extreme opponents without inflaming the debate still
further by raising their own voices.
If mainstream Flemish politicians and businesspeople are to be believed,
Flanders is on the brink of a new era of prosperity, built on the same basis
as the Flemish booms of the middle ages and the 16th and 17th centuries:
location and trade.
The geographical bad luck which brought German and allied armies together in
northern Belgium during the Great War, is now a boon. More than half the
population of the EC lives within 500 miles of Antwerp, Flanders' first city
and principal port. Flanders is less than half the (limited) territory of
Belgium, and well over half the population - but its borders are open and
transport infrastructure is good.
Flanders' roads, waterways and railways help export 75 per cent of what the
region's companies make. In some sectors, such as basic metals and textiles,
nearer 80 per cent of what is produced is sold beyond Belgium's borders. Per
capita, Belgium is the largest car exporter in the world: Flanders is a
production base for Ford, Volkswagen and Volvo; Ghent and Antwerp provide
distribution centres for Honda and Mazda respectively.
But because it is responsible for 70 per cent of all Belgian exports,
Flanders is a very sensitive barometer of the state of the European economy
and world trade, and the region's great ports are its needle. As Mr Jan
Devroe, president of the Antwerp Port Authority, puts it: 'Everything which
affects the free market and limits it, affects us.'
For the time being, recession is taking the shine off the golden passport.
Unemployment in Flanders is running at a lower rate than in the poorer
region of Wallonia, but it is growing faster, as the foreign companies which
are among Flanders' largest employers begin to cut back. Public investment
is at a historic low across Belgium.
To the frustration of even moderate Flemish politicians and economists, the
far-reaching reforms of the Belgian constitution which will formally change
the country into a federal state, will give little new fiscal and financial
autonomy to the regional government.
Instead, the reforms are whetting Flemings' appetite for even more
independence, part of a continuous and sometimes painful process of
emancipation which began almost as soon as Belgium was declared independent
in 1830.
This tendency is easily exaggerated. For example, Flemish politicians from
the main political parties cast doubt on the simplistic perception that the
constitutional changes will inevitably precipitate an acrimonious break-up
of Belgium, creating a west European parallel for the Czech-Slovak split.
'There is a basic conviction that the largest powers will go to the north
and the south, but there's also a major part of the Flemish population which
says we should maintain the kingdom,' explains Mr Luc Van den Brande,
minister-president of the Flemish government - a coalition of socialists and
Christian Democrats like the national administration.
If Belgium is to achieve this peaceful goal, however, there will have to be
a great deal more co-operation between the regions than has been evident to
date. Diplomatic relations within Belgium often seem to be trickier than
between regions and third countries.
In recent months, for example, Mr Van den Brande has managed to arrange
talks with the prime minister of the Netherlands in The Hague, but he and
his Walloon and Bruxellois counterparts have struggled to organise a meeting
in their own country.
If internal relations do break down, then it is clear that Flemings and
Walloons will be only too ready to blame one another for the disintegration
of the state. Mr Guy Verhofstadt, leader of the opposition Flemish liberal
democrats - now Flanders' most popular party - warns that financial
imbalances between the two regional economies could be the catalyst for a
split: 'If there is not a will to start up a new dialogue between the
regions and communities about the financial problems in this country I think
you will see a growth of separatism in this country in the next few years.'
That would play into the hands of extremists on both sides of the Belgian
linguistic divide, but particularly in Flanders, where the far-right Vlaams
Blok party gained a shocking 10.4 per cent of the regional vote at the last
national elections in 1991.
The vote was partly an expression of discontent with the political
establishment, but it also reflected many ordinary Flemings' suspicion of
the openness which has characterised Belgium and Flanders since the second
world war, a suspicion now being fuelled by recession.
That is part of the reason why the Flemish government has pinned its hopes
on an outward-looking strategy which 'appeals to the Flemish population to
work towards a new Flanders in Europe.'
Interestingly, Vlaams Blok also talks about the region's future in European
terms. But when Mr Karel Dillen, a Blok Euro-MP, says he wants to 'make
Flanders European' - as he did at last month's session of the European
Parliament - he means he wants to expel non-EC immigrants, many of whom,
ironically, were brought in as cheap labour by Flemish companies during the
booming 1960s.
Mr Van den Brande rejects such calls-to-arms. 'We're trying to mobilise our
population, instead of regressing and building a new wall around Flanders.
It's essential that we're open to other cultures,' he says.
But what is already clear is that Flemings will never be comfortable with a
strong international economic identity, if it is won at the expense of
Flanders' vibrant historical and cultural heritage.
</TEXT>
<XX>
