<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Falling bond yields spur late
buying surge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
A BURST of late buying lifted US share prices across the board yesterday.
Earlier, the markets had struggled to make headway after news of a decline
in manufacturing activity raised fresh doubts over the strength of the
economic recovery, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 18.91 at 3,446.46. The
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 gained 2.27 at 442.46, while the American SE composite
finished 1.25 firmer at 422.21 and the Nasdaq composite 5.29 stronger at
666.71. Trading volume on the New York SE came to 225m shares.
The markets opened the week in a cautious mood. The first-quarter reporting
season proved that corporate profitability is improving, but a slew of
recent evidence suggesting that economic growth is slowing down has clouded
the outlook for future earnings.
Yesterday's economic data was especially disturbing. The National
Association of Purchasing Management reported that its index of business
activity fell to 49.7 per cent in April, from the 53.4 per cent of the
previous month. A measure below 50 per cent is indicative of a contracting
manufacturing sector, and it is the first time the index has been below 50
per cent since September 1992.
Coupled with news of a small decline in March construction spending, the
NAPM added to investors' concern about the state of the economy. A rise in
bond prices triggered by the NAPM, however, helped stocks to stay in
positive territory for most of the day, and a subsequent fall in bond yields
spurred a surge of buying in the final hours of trading.
Among individual stocks, Eastman Kodak, which has suffered recently because
of the turmoil among the company's top management, rose Dollars  7/8 to
Dollars 49 5/8 in busy trading after Kodak's independent board of directors
called for a significant improvement in the company's performance, a call
that was seen as backing for Kodak's chairman, Mr Kay Whitmore.
Minnesota Mining &amp; Manufacturing rose Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 113 1/2 after
the company unveiled first-quarter net income of Dollars 1.51 a share, up
from Dollars 1.38 a share a year earlier.
Among the main beneficiaries of the late buying were motor and drug shares.
General Motors climbed Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 42 1/4 , Ford added Dollars
1 1/8 at Dollars 55 7/8 and Chrysler firmed Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 42 1/8 .
In the drugs sector, Merck advanced Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 38 1/4 , Pfizer
Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 69 3/4 and Johnson &amp; Johnson Dollars 1 3/8 to
Dollars 44 7/8 .
Bethlehem Steel put on Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 19 7/8 in busy trading after
the company said it would increase its steel and alloy plate products prices
on July 4 to recover manufacturing costs.
On the Nasdaq market, Chiron jumped Dollars 3 3/4 to Dollars 58 on news that
in recent tests a herpes vaccine produced by the company in a joint venture
with Ciba-Geigy was shown to significantly reduce the frequency of
outbreaks.
Canada
TORONTO closed lower in heavy trading as gold stocks gave back a big chunk
of last week's gains.
The TSE 300 index fell 15.9 to 3,773.5 and declining issues outnumbered
advances by 371 to 327 after volume of 55.7m shares valued at CDollars
550.3m.
Nine of the 14 stock groups lost ground, led by the golds sector, off 3.5
per cent.
</TEXT>
