FT  04 MAY 93 / International Company News: Northwest Air in two union deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NORTHWEST Airlines, the fourth largest US carrier which is currently
integrating operations with Europe's KLM Royal Dutch Airlines, announced
yesterday that it had secured an 'agreement in principle' with two major
unions over key work-rule and pay concessions.
Details of the agreement, which is subject to ratification, were not made
public. However, two months ago, Northwest offered employees a 20 per cent
equity interest in the company if they would provide cost savings of about
Dollars 883m over a three-year period. The cost-savings were seen as
critical to the US airline's future, and there has been speculation that it
might file for bankruptcy protection if the wage concessions were not
forthcoming.
Yesterday's deal was struck with the International Association of Machinists
and the International Brotherhood of Teamsters, representing the mechanics
and flight attendants respectively. The major employee group which has not
yet struck a deal is the Air Line Pilots Association. Three other unions
also remain in negotiation with the carrier.
