<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
How odd that Michael Buerk, whom I associate with really worthwhile
reporting, has got himself enmeshed in 999 (9.40 BBC1). This is tabloid TV,
tales of heroism and bravery re-enacted. Perhaps the powers that be see this
as the way forward, the low-brow and down-market made more palatable by
hauling in respected faces.
Forty Minutes (9.50, BBC2) visits an army training camp in Australia where
women volunteers learn not to sleep with their teddy-bears if they want to
join 31 Platoon. Conceivably this is the first such programme to explore how
Army training rescues a bunch of women from the decadence of civvy street
and transforms them into disciplined, motivated, worthwhile human beings.
Maiden Voyages (8.30 C4) is also about a woman rediscovering herself in
Australia. A single-parent mum who brought up children in her teens on a
Manchester council estate, flies to Australia and hires a motorbike. She
rides across the outback and feels free and generally uplifted. Meanwhile on
BBC2, Delia Smith finds fulfilment of a more traditional kind.
</TEXT>
<XX>
